args: Raywall's great strength is a thing of the\npast, seeing how easily we were able to\nmake our way across her border.
It has been more than ten years since the\nceasefire. There are few still vigilant after\nall this time.
So they're nothing without their key\ngeneral, then.
You have no doubts about the situation\nwith him, I trust?

He was transferred to the royal capital
several days ago and is presently on the
journey. Whatever happens in Raywall
will take place without his presence.
Raywall's capitulation will now be easier\nthan taking sweets from a child.
Framing the linchpin of the Raywall army\nas an insurrectionist and banishing him\nfrom the city was a clever plan.
I was skeptical at first, but it seems to\nhave worked out rather nicely.
The plan took several years to form and\nexecute; I should be quite distraught\nhad it not gone to perfection.
How unfortunate that I have to see you\nin such a sad state.
I've been shadowing you all along.\nBlending into the darkness is something\nof a forte of meowne.
You're not going to try and explain your\nway out of it at this late stage, are you?
It is clear you are colluding with Grams\nin order to sell out Raywall.
But why? Your will to protect Raywall felt\ntrue, so why have you done this thing?
I do it TO protect her!
I may have fomented this unrest, but it is\nnonetheless true that Raywall seeks war.
The tide is inevitable, and there is little\nI can do to hold it back at this point.
Even without my actions, Raywall and\nGrams would have gone to war eventually.
So you sought to make Raywall fall to\nGrams before the war could even begin?
Just so. If war were to ever break out,\nlives would be lost and the city set to burn.
To save Raywall, I have no recourse but to\nput her in a state where war cannot occur.
Do you understand the consequences\nsuch a plan could incur?
The army of Grams will not be satisfied\nwith Raywall alone, and the flames of war\nwill soon lick at all Alberia.
You would save Raywall at the expense\nof some other city elsewhere.
Then you don't care at all for what might\nhappen beyond your city walls?!

I know what you will say: Such a thing is
cruel. Unjust, and despicable, and you
would not have me impose tragedy upon
others in order to spare ourselves.
Yet that is exactly what happened to US\nall those years ago!

WE were the only ones engulfed in the
flames fanned by the previous war!
The whole of the nation leaned on our
strength and gained from our sacrifice!
That is why I swore a vow to give all that I\nam to protect this city and territory from\nsuch a cruel fate ever again.
No matter the injustices I may have to\nperpetrate, or the dishonor I may be\nforced to weather.
Are you disappointed, Princess Chelle?\nYou ought to understand.
Nobility has a duty to bear responsibility\nfor their people—to protect their lives and\nlivelihoods. Is that not so?
It is. Nobility is not merely something to\nbe relished, but a status that brings with it\nthe responsibility to safeguard others.
You admit to caring not a whit for what\noccurs outside Raywall, which means\nyour nobility ends at the city gates.
If I am disappointed, it is not because of\nyour cruelty, but your limited ambition!
You have surpassed me, my fiancée.
You possess such a small view of yourself,\nLord Elua. You know this, yes?
Even if there were truth to that, I will not\ngive credit to my own capabilities at this\npoint—so let this serve as our farewell.
Yes. Pray forgive me for the delay.\nYou may now deploy your troops to\nRaywall as we previously arranged.
Being discovered by Princess Chelle was a\nblunder, but even were she to raise a fuss,\nall will be over and done with by then.

You'll likely leap to this conclusion soon,
but I'll save you the trouble and just admit
that I halted the transfer of the general
to the capital.
You cannot possibly believe I came here\nwithout any sort of plan?

Unfortunately for you, I am not such a
romantic that I believed I could put a
stop to your machinations with the power
of love.
Nor am I here empty-handed, Marquis—\nyou will find I lead a considerable force\nof every man and woman I could mobilize.
Even if your forces were to attack them\nhead-on, I rather like our chances.
And on that note, Lord Caspar,\nmight you care to make a deal?
I assume you do not wish to start a war\nwith Raywall at this time, correct?
In that case, perhaps it might be better\nto decide that it never happened?
Why, the Grams army having crossed the\nnational border, of course! I would decide\nthat such a transgression never happened.

That rests entirely on you—but I would
suggest that our good relations continuing
on as they have in the past would be
reward enough.
Indeed. I shall send along invitations\nto parties once more.
It would seem you are better at this game\nthan the Marquis of Raywall...\nVery well, Princess. All troops, withdraw!
I will be transferring you to the capital\nso you might face the judgment of the\nroyal court.
Poetic justice, I suppose—but I am ready\nfor whatever decision they may hand down.
I wish only that I had met you sooner,\nLord Elua. If so, perhaps...
Stop. You mustn't have such regrets.\nAll of this was brought on by the\nmeagerness of my abilities alone.
Forget about this man lacking in ambition,\nand continue to walk forward with nobility\nand grace, Princess.
That would be a small solace for me.
...My, but time does fly.\nHow meowny years has it been?
But now that Chanzelia has finally come\ntogether, is it really the right time to up\nand abandon the territory?
It may well scatter once more in your\nabsence, sad as that is to contemplate.

Goodness, do you think I have been
cultivating an organization that can
be taken down in the mere absence
of a ruler or two?
And besides, this will be the perfect\nopportunity. Certainly, my priorities\nlie with {player_name}, but...
I was just thinking it was time to thank the\npeople of the Holy City of Grams for what\nhappened that day... Eee hee hee!
*sigh* I know not what will occur in the\nnorth, but it sounds as if it certainly will\nnot be boring.
And I wouldn't have it any other way.\nNow let us be off, Cat Sìth!
I've wanted to ask you this for some time:\nWhy did you change the name from\nRaywall to Chanzelia?
Because Raywall was the name of\na traitor.
And I believed it would be better to\nerase such a thing entirely.
For I must continue to walk forward\nwith nobility and grace.
